2026, day 176

Good morning from Asia.

‘How Iran Devastated an American Naval Base—and Caused a U.S. Recalculation’ (WSJ);

‘Iran Attacks Cargo Ship, Testing Trump’s Deal to Reopen Strait’ (WSJ) - “Attack takes place hours after Iranian warning to ships not to use routes that the regime hadn’t sanctioned”;

‘UN pauses Hormuz evacuation plan after ship reports attack’ (Al Arabiya);

‘Iran Estimates $40 Billion Windfall From Reopening Hormuz With Gulf States’ (WSJ);

‘Vance announces unprecedented CENTCOM-IRGC talks aimed at reducing military tensions’ (JPost);

‘Gulf FMs say Iran proxies, missiles must be addressed for ‘lasting’ peace’ (Al Arabiya);

‘Israel attacks Lebanon as Netanyahu says troops to stay’ (AJ);

‘Israel says will only withdraw troops from Lebanon after Hezbollah disarmed’ (AFP);

‘Quds force commander demands Israel leave Lebanon as Iran's deputy FM threatens Italy, Romania’ (JPost);

‘Trump claims he stopped ‘great leader’ Erdogan from bringing Turkey into war on Iran’s side’ (ToI);

‘Despite objections, Trump notifies US Congress of $700M jet engine sale to Turkey’ (Reuters);

‘The final frontier: Israel aims to become world leader in space attack capabilities, Katz says’ (JPost);

‘‘As Ukraine seizes ‘first chance to win’, war horrors come home to Russia’ (AJ);

‘Putin risks public fury with army call-up’ (Telegraph) - “Moscow considers mobilisation drive amid a drop in recruits and high fatalities”;

‘Macron says France intercepted a Russian shadow fleet oil tanker off coast of Sicily’ (Euronews);

‘NATO allies to pledge billions in arms deals, Ukraine aid at Ankara summit ‘ (Politico) - “They are also considering references to the U.S. war in Iran as part of the draft summit declaration”;

‘NATO’s Rutte gave confused account of Italy’s involvement in Iran war, Meloni says’ (Politico);

‘Britain’s ‘senior Nato role at risk without defence spending increase’’ (Telegraph);

‘Polish opposition seeks to block Ukraine’s EU bid’ (FT);

‘Trump backs ‘Six Assurances’ to Taiwan but no arms sale timeline, US diplomat says’ (SCMP);

‘US defense spending demand leaves Asian allies in limbo’ (Nikkei Asia) - “White House call for minimum defense budget of 3.5% of GDP is far above what most can achieve anytime soon”;

In geoeconomics, ‘Brussels tightens rules on US cloud providers as it pushes for tech sovereignty’ (Euronews);

‘Cheat sheet for an EU financial geopolitics plan’ (FT) - “How to become an autonomous global power in monetary matters”;

‘Brussels picks up pace on Draghi economic reform agenda’ (FT) - “new assessment argues EU has implemented ~30% of recommendations”;

‘US assures India over AI ‘kill switch’ as ‘Pax Silica’ expands in bid to counter China’ (SCMP);

‘Chinese firms brace for new EU rules as trade deficit tops $1bn a day’ (Nikkei Asia) - “Bloc leaders ready diversification tool but still split on how hard to push Beijing”;

‘Trump administration asks OpenAI to limit next model release’ (Axios);

‘‘Do or die’ for small carmakers: China market braces for 156 new models as price war looms’ (SCMP);

‘Canada must be ready to cut a USMCA deal if one arises, Carney says’ (Globe & Mail);

‘Indonesia Opens Door to Dirty Money to Fund Prabowo’s Plans’ (BBG) - “Indonesia's sovereign wealth fund, Danantara, is offering unprecedented legal protections for investors, including immunity from criminal, civil or tax probes”;

In politics, ‘Supreme Court lets Trump end deportation protections for Haitians and Syrians’ (Reuters);

‘US judge blocks Trump's executive order restricting mail-in voting’ (Reuters);

‘Postal Service Plans Not to Deliver Mail Ballots to States Unless They Hand Over Voter Data’ (Time);

‘Andy Burnham planning new ‘devolution department’ in Manchester’ (FT);

In markets, ‘Oil Holds Gain as Traders Weigh Hormuz Flows After Ship Attack’ (BBG);

‘The ever weirder world of venture capital’ (FT);

‘Gold has crashed back to earth. Here’s what to do next’ (AFR)
